(a) **general semaphore** - A synchronization primitive (counter) that can be incremented (signal/V) or decremented (wait/P) to control access to shared resources. It can have any non-negative integer value, not just 0 or 1.

(b) **best fit** - A memory allocation algorithm that searches for the smallest available memory block that is large enough to satisfy the allocation request, minimizing internal fragmentation.

(c) **supervisor mode** - A privileged CPU execution mode used by the operating system kernel where all instructions (including I/O and memory management operations) are allowed; contrasts with user mode which is restricted.

(d) **race condition** - A situation where the behavior of a concurrent program depends on the relative timing of operations on shared data, potentially leading to incorrect results.

(e) **multiprogramming** - A technique where multiple processes share the CPU and other system resources, with the OS switching between them to allow apparent concurrent execution.

