## Question 1: Short Definitions

**(a) General Semaphore**
A general semaphore is a synchronization primitive consisting of an integer counter that can be incremented (signal/V operation) or decremented (wait/P operation) to control access to shared resources, where the counter can take any non-negative integer value and processes block when attempting to decrement below zero.

**(b) Best Fit**
Best fit is a memory allocation algorithm that searches for the smallest available free memory block that is large enough to satisfy an allocation request, thereby minimizing internal fragmentation.

**(c) Supervisor Mode**
Supervisor mode is a privileged CPU execution mode in which the operating system kernel runs and all machine instructions (including I/O operations and memory management instructions) are permitted to execute.

**(d) Race Condition**
A race condition is a situation in a concurrent program where the final result depends on the relative timing or ordering of operations by multiple processes on shared data, potentially leading to unpredictable or incorrect behavior.

**(e) Multiprogramming**
Multiprogramming is a technique in which multiple processes share the CPU and other system resources, with the operating system rapidly switching between them to create the illusion of parallel execution.

